    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: Dynamic Events (Optional - if you have time)
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "<i>The following steps are just for people who are interested
          and have time</i>.\r\nYou may recall in the UI practical the concept of
          <b>Dynamic Events</b>. In UI, this was used for events where the new value
          of an InputField was passed through as a string, or the new value of a
          Slider was passed through as a float parameter. We can do the same with
          custom events to simplify the usage of the TripWire events.\r\n<b>Remove
          the two event listeners from the TripWire by using the \"-\" button.</b>\r\nThe
          two <c>UnityEvent</c>s we made only handle basic, \"Static\" events. To
          use a Dynamic event, we need to add a new class which defines the event
          (just like we have added new classes to add new MonoBehaviour scripts).
          \r\n<b>In the TripWire.cs code, add the following code to the top of the
          file (outside the TripWire class):</b>\r\n<code>\r\n[System.Serializable]\r\npublic
          class OnRaycastChangeEvent : UnityEvent&lt;bool> { }\r\n</code>\r\n(note
          the use of System.Serializable\u2014this makes it so that the event listener
          will appear in the Unity inspector)\r\nThe defines a new type of <c>UnityEvent</c>,
          that takes a single Boolean parameter when it is used in dynamic mode.
          For this event, the Boolean parameter will tell the event listener whether
          or not the tripwire is <b>un-broken</b> or not (if this logic seems backwards
          to you\u2014i.e. we should return true if the tripwire is broken\u2014then
          I agree with you, however it makes the latter part of this step a lot simpler).\r\n<b>Add
          a new public variable to the TripWire class using this new event type:</b>\r\n<code>\r\npublic
          OnRaycastChangeEvent onTripWireStateChange;\r\n</code>\r\nInvoking this
          new event type is the same as invoking the normal events, except we need
          to pass through the <i>dynamic parameter</i> when we <c>Invoke()</c> it.
          \r\n<b>Add the following line to the end of the Update function:</b>\r\n<code>\r\nonTripWireStateChange.Invoke(hitObject.collider
          == null);\r\n</code>\r\n(When <c>hitObject.collider</c> is null, then the
          tripwire is complete and untouched by the player/enemies)\r\n<b>Save the
          file and return to Unity. </b>\r\n<b>Add a new event listener to the OnTripWireStateChanged
          event which targets the SecretWall, but this time select the \"dynamic\"
          listener version of SetActive():</b>\r"
